President Cyril Ramaphosa has again called for an end to gender-based violence and femicide. Courtesy of #DStv403  JOHANNESBURG - As the country commemorates the 65th anniversary of the adoption of the Freedom Charter, ANC president Cyril Ramaphosa has called for an end to gender-based violence and femicide. This as the body count continues to rise. READ: Ramaphosa on GBV: SA is fighting another pandemic Ramaphosa says the war on women and children is a travesty and has called on South Africans to take a stand. READ: Femicide in the spotlight South Africa "It is a travesty that women and children in the country feel unsafe," Ramaphosa said. Ramaphosa said government is strengthening the criminal justice system to more effectively deal with gender-based violence. "We need all of society to work together to effectively deal with gender-based violence and all other social ills," Ramaphosa said.